// C3: Physical Sensing Components
instance InternalTemperatureSensor1 : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "First of two high-resolution analog temperature sensors monitoring the internal environment of the styrofoam box incubator. Transmits real-time temperature readings (likely in °C or °F) with periodic polling frequency (1-10 seconds) via serial (UART), I2C, or SPI interface from Raspberry Pi controller."
    DTDFVocab:producedData InternalTemperatureDataTransmitted1
]

instance InternalTemperatureSensor2 : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Second of two high-resolution analog temperature sensors monitoring the internal environment of the styrofoam box incubator. Transmits real-time temperature readings (likely in °C or °F) with periodic polling frequency (1-10 seconds) via serial (UART), I2C, or SPI interface from Raspberry Pi controller."
    DTDFVocab:producedData InternalTemperatureDataTransmitted2
]

instance ExternalTemperatureSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Single high-resolution analog temperature sensor monitoring the external ambient environment of the styrofoam box incubator. Transmits real-time temperature readings (likely in °C or °F) with periodic polling frequency (1-10 seconds) via serial (UART), I2C, or SPI interface from Raspberry Pi controller."
    DTDFVocab:producedData ExternalTemperatureDataTransmitted
]

// C4: Physical-to-Virtual Interaction
instance InternalTemperatureDataTransmitted1 : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    base:desc "Raw analog temperature data from InternalTemperatureSensor1 transmitted via cyber-physical system integration protocol (UART/I2C/SPI) with periodic polling (1-10 seconds). Undergoes normalization and outlier filtering before integration into digital twin models."
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom InternalTemperatureSensor1
]

instance InternalTemperatureDataTransmitted2 : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    base:desc "Raw analog temperature data from InternalTemperatureSensor2 transmitted via cyber-physical system integration protocol (UART/I2C/SPI) with periodic polling (1-10 seconds). Undergoes normalization and outlier filtering before integration into digital twin models."
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom InternalTemperatureSensor2
]

instance ExternalTemperatureDataTransmitted : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    base:desc "Raw analog temperature data from ExternalTemperatureSensor transmitted via cyber-physical system integration protocol (UART/I2C/SPI) with periodic polling (1-10 seconds). Undergoes normalization and outlier filtering before integration into digital twin models."
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom ExternalTemperatureSensor
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance TwoParameterThermalModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Dynamic thermal model of the incubator system with two free parameters describing heat transfer characteristics. Used for simulating thermal behavior and predicting temperature distribution within the styrofoam box."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo CalibrationAlgorithm, StateEstimator
]

instance FourParameterThermalModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Enhanced dynamic thermal model of the incubator system with four free parameters providing superior predictive accuracy for thermal inertia of the heatbed. Used for high-fidelity simulations and control optimization."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo CalibrationAlgorithm, StateEstimator, FaultDetector
]

instance NormalizedInternalTemperatureData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Processed internal temperature data from both internal sensors after normalization, outlier removal, and noise filtering. Used as input for model calibration and state estimation."
    DTDFVocab:fromData InternalTemperatureDataTransmitted1, InternalTemperatureDataTransmitted2
    DTDFVocab:inputTo CalibrationAlgorithm, StateEstimator
]

instance NormalizedExternalTemperatureData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Processed external temperature data from ambient sensor after normalization, outlier removal, and noise filtering. Used as input for model calibration and environmental condition assessment."
    DTDFVocab:fromData ExternalTemperatureDataTransmitted
    DTDFVocab:inputTo CalibrationAlgorithm, StateEstimator
]

instance ThermalGradientData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Derived data representing temperature gradients between internal and external environments calculated from normalized sensor data. Used for thermal performance analysis and fault detection."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo FaultDetector, OptimizationAlgorithm
]

// C11: Enablers
instance CalibrationAlgorithm : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Algorithm that updates model parameters (TwoParameterThermalModel and FourParameterThermalModel) using real-time sensor data to minimize discrepancies between physical and digital twin representations. Implements differential equation-based calibration."
    DTDFVocab:enables TemperatureMonitoringService, PredictiveSimulationService, AnomalyDetectionService
]

instance StateEstimator : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Estimates current thermal state of the physical incubator using sensor data and calibrated models. Provides real-time system state for control and monitoring purposes with confidence measures derived from model calibration accuracy."
    DTDFVocab:enables TemperatureMonitoringService, ControlService
]

instance FaultDetector : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Monitors system performance for anomalies by analyzing thermal gradient data and model predictions. Triggers alerts or corrective actions when deviations exceed safety or performance thresholds."
    DTDFVocab:enables AnomalyDetectionService, ControlService
]

instance OptimizationAlgorithm : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Adjusts control parameters (heatbed power, fan speed) dynamically to achieve optimal temperature regulation with minimal energy consumption. Uses calibrated models and real-time data to suggest improvements."
    DTDFVocab:enables OptimizationService, ControlService
]

// C6: Services
instance TemperatureMonitoringService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Continuous real-time monitoring of the incubator's internal and external temperature using processed sensor data. Provides detection of anomalies or deviations from expected thermal behavior."
    DTDFVocab:provides RealTimeTemperatureInsight, TemperatureDeviationAlertAction
]

instance PredictiveSimulationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Running simulations to reproduce and predict the incubator's thermal behavior under current or hypothetical operating conditions. Enables proactive decision-making for temperature regulation."
    DTDFVocab:provides ThermalBehaviorPredictionInsight, PreemptiveControlAction
]

instance AnomalyDetectionService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Identifies violations of safety or performance thresholds through analysis of thermal gradients and model predictions. Triggers alerts or automated corrective actions for system adjustments."
    DTDFVocab:provides FaultConditionInsight, CorrectiveAction
]

instance OptimizationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Optimizes the incubator's performance to achieve desired temperature regulation with minimal energy consumption. Adjusts control parameters dynamically based on real-time data and model predictions."
    DTDFVocab:provides EnergyEfficiencyInsight, ParameterAdjustmentAction
]

instance ControlService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Supervisory control ensuring the system operates safely and optimally. Implements fault detection, corrective actions, and automated decision-making for temperature regulation."
    DTDFVocab:provides SystemHealthInsight, ControlAdjustmentAction
]

// C17: Insights/Actions
instance RealTimeTemperatureInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Current internal and external temperature readings with confidence measures derived from model calibration accuracy and sensor reliability."
]

instance TemperatureDeviationAlertAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Alerts operators or triggers automated corrective actions when temperature deviations exceed predefined thresholds."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance ThermalBehaviorPredictionInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Predicted thermal behavior of the incubator under current or hypothetical conditions, including potential overheating or cooling scenarios."
]

instance PreemptiveControlAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Adjusts control parameters (heatbed power, fan speed) proactively to prevent overheating or cooling failures based on predictive simulations."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance FaultConditionInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Identified anomalies or faults in the system based on thermal gradient analysis and model predictions, including confidence levels."
]

instance CorrectiveAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated or operator-triggered corrective actions to restore system to safe operating conditions (e.g., adjusting heatbed/fan settings)."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic false
]

instance EnergyEfficiencyInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Optimized energy consumption metrics and temperature regulation efficiency based on real-time data and model predictions."
]

instance ParameterAdjustmentAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Dynamic adjustment of control parameters (heatbed power, fan speed) to maintain optimal temperature regulation with minimal energy usage."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance SystemHealthInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Comprehensive assessment of the incubator's current health status, including thermal performance, fault conditions, and operational stability."
]

instance ControlAdjustmentAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "High-level control decisions based on digital twin insights, including fault detection responses and system reconfiguration."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

// C1: System Components
instance InsulatedContainer : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Styrofoam box used to maintain temperature stability inside the incubator system. Acts as the primary insulated environment for thermal regulation."
]

instance Heatbed : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Heating element responsible for raising and maintaining the temperature inside the insulated container. Thermal inertia characteristics are modeled with four free parameters for high-fidelity simulation."
]

instance Fan : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Distributes heat evenly inside the container to ensure uniform temperature distribution and prevent thermal gradients."
]

instance RaspberryPiController : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Acts as the controller for the incubator system, managing inputs from temperature sensors and outputs to heatbed and fan. Runs control algorithms and facilitates cyber-physical system integration."
]

instance DigitalTwinFramework : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Generic digital twin framework integrating modeling, simulation, monitoring, and optimization technologies. Enables real-time interaction between physical and digital twins."
]

// C2: Acting Components
instance HeatbedActuator : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Actuates the heating element to adjust internal temperature based on control signals from the digital twin. Receives power modulation commands for precise temperature regulation."
]

instance FanActuator : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Controls fan speed to distribute heat evenly and maintain uniform temperature within the insulated container. Adjusts based on thermal gradient data and control algorithms."
]

// C5: Environment
instance IncubatorEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:desc "Closed, insulated environment for temperature regulation and control within the incubator system. Includes internal and external thermal conditions affecting system behavior."
    base:contains InsulatedContainer, Heatbed, Fan, InternalTemperatureSensor1, InternalTemperatureSensor2, ExternalTemperatureSensor
]

instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin (DT) exerts **control commands** back to the Physical Twin (PT) via the **Raspberry Pi**, which acts as the intermediary controller. The **command types** include **setpoint adjustments** for the **heatbed** (e.g., PWM signals to regulate heating power) and potentially **fan speed modulation** (if controlled digitally). The **control message format** is unspecified but likely follows a **structured protocol** (e.g., JSON, binary payloads, or direct register writes) transmitted over the same interface used for sensor data (e.g., UART/I2C). **Validation and authentication mechanisms** are **not detailed**, though the DT’s **calibration algorithms** implicitly validate commands by ensuring the PT’s response aligns with predicted behavior. **Feedback systems** operate via the **closed-loop control architecture**: the DT’s monitors detect deviations (e.g., temperature drift) and trigger corrective actions, while the PT’s sensors provide **real-time feedback** to the DT for continuous adjustment. **Conflict resolution** is handled by the **supervisory controller** (either human or algorithmic), which prioritizes safety-critical commands (e.g., emergency cooling) over routine adjustments. **Command execution confirmation** is inferred through the **monitoring loop**, where the DT verifies the PT’s state post-command via sensor data to confirm compliance with the intended control action."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system operates with a **real-time synchronization paradigm**, where data from the Physical Twin (PT) is continuously collected via sensors (e.g., temperature sensors in the incubator case study) and fed into the Digital Twin (DT) for calibration and analysis. The temporal granularity depends on the **sampling frequency of the sensors** and the **latency requirements of the monitoring and control algorithms**. For instance, in the incubator example, temperature sensors provide **continuous or high-frequency updates** (exact frequency not specified but implied to be near real-time for effective regulation). The DT employs **calibration algorithms** to update its models (e.g., differential equations for dynamic behavior) with the latest sensor data, ensuring the DT's state aligns with the PT's operational conditions. Latency constraints are critical for **fault detection, supervisory control, and state estimation**, where delays could lead to suboptimal or unsafe decisions. The system must balance **accuracy** (requiring frequent updates) with **computational efficiency** (as high-fidelity models may slow down analysis)."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system follows a **cyber-physical system (CPS)-based architecture**, where the DT integrates **three core components**: (1) **Data** (collected from PT sensors in real-time), (2) **Models** (representing the cyber and physical aspects of the PT and its environment, including differential equations for dynamic behavior), and (3) **Algorithms** (e.g., calibration algorithms, fault detectors, supervisory controllers, and optimizers). The orchestration is depicted in **Figure 1**, where the DT employs a **closed-loop control structure**: sensor data is used to **calibrate models** of the CPS and environment, generating updated parameters. These parameters inform **monitors** that evaluate system safety and optimality. If violations are detected, **human or algorithmic interventions** can adjust the PT (e.g., modifying control inputs). The architecture supports **resource management** through prioritization of critical services (e.g., real-time monitoring vs. offline optimization) and **component integration** via standardized interfaces for data flow and algorithm execution. The system-wide coordination relies on **tight coupling** between cyber and physical layers, ensuring the DT's predictions and actions are aligned with the PT's operational state."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin (DT) lifecycle in the provided context includes the following phases: **(1) Model Development**: Abstract representations of the Physical Twin (PT) are created at varying levels of abstraction (e.g., CAD models for geometric properties or dynamic models described by differential equations for behavioral analysis). These models may include cyber-physical aspects (e.g., control logic, sensor data processing) and physical aspects (e.g., thermal dynamics, mechanical forces). **(2) Integration with Physical Twin**: During deployment, models are retained and integrated into the DT framework, enabling real-time synchronization with the PT via sensor-collected data. **(3) Calibration and Validation**: The DT employs **calibration algorithms** to update models with real-time data, ensuring alignment between the virtual and physical systems. This phase involves iterative refinement of model parameters (e.g., thermal conductivity in the incubator case study) to minimize prediction errors. **(4) Operational Monitoring**: The DT continuously monitors the PT’s performance using **monitors** (e.g., fault detectors, state estimators) to identify deviations from optimal/safe conditions. **(5) Adaptive Reconfiguration**: When violations or inefficiencies are detected, the DT triggers corrective actions (e.g., adjusting control parameters or alerting human operators), leveraging **supervisory controllers** or automated algorithms. **(6) Evolution and Retirement**: The DT supports **reconfigurability** to adapt to environmental changes (e.g., varying thermal loads in the incubator) and may undergo lifecycle governance to ensure compliance with evolving system requirements or standards. Transition management between phases relies on **data-driven feedback loops**, where sensor inputs (e.g., temperature readings from the incubator’s internal/external sensors) inform model updates and decision-making processes."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model **fidelity** in the Digital Twin is ensured through **validation and verification (V&V) methods**, including comparative analysis of simulation outputs against real-world PT behavior. In the incubator case study, the **four-parameter model** was empirically validated as superior for predicting thermal inertia, demonstrating higher fidelity than the two-parameter model. **Uncertainty sources** include discrepancies between modeled and actual PT dynamics, addressed via **calibration algorithms** that iteratively refine model parameters using sensor data. **Error detection and correction** mechanisms involve monitors that flag deviations from optimal/safe performance, triggering human or algorithmic interventions (e.g., adjusting actuators in the PT). **Quality assurance** processes rely on continuous model-data alignment, with the DT framework enabling **real-time diagnostics** and **predictive analytics** to mitigate errors. The incubator study highlights the importance of **experimental validation** to select models with higher predictive accuracy for DT development."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin (DT) of the incubator relies on a **cyber-physical system (CPS) architecture** where the **Raspberry Pi** serves as the **edge computing node** bridging the PT and DT. The **communication protocols** are **not explicitly specified**, but the system implies **low-latency, high-reliability links** (e.g., Ethernet, Wi-Fi, or direct serial connections) between the Pi and the DT’s hosting environment. The **network topology** is likely **star-shaped**, with the Pi as the central hub collecting sensor data and dispatching commands. **Bandwidth requirements** are minimal (likely <1 Mbps) due to the **low-frequency, low-data-rate sensor streams**, but **latency must be sub-second** to ensure real-time calibration and control. **Reliability mechanisms** include **redundant sensor readings** (two internal temperature sensors) and **fault-tolerant algorithms** (e.g., consensus-based calibration). **Security protocols** are **not mentioned**, though in a real-world deployment, measures like **TLS for data-in-transit encryption**, **authenticated API endpoints**, and **access control** would be critical to prevent spoofing or unauthorized command injection."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin (DT) for the incubator is deployed in a **hybrid edge-cloud model**, with the **Raspberry Pi handling real-time processing** (e.g., sensor data acquisition, preliminary calibration, and control execution) and a **centralized cloud/on-premise server** managing **long-term analytics, model updates, and high-fidelity simulations**. The **computational requirements** are **lightweight** for edge operations (e.g., running lightweight Python scripts or embedded C++ for control loops) but may scale to **medium-high** for cloud-based tasks (e.g., solving differential equations or training ML models for predictive maintenance). **Storage requirements** are minimal for edge nodes but grow for cloud storage, where **historical sensor data, model versions, and simulation logs** are retained. **Scalability mechanisms** are **not detailed**, though the modular design (e.g., separate models for cyber/physical components) suggests **plug-and-play extensibility** for additional sensors or actuators. The **deployment model** supports **continuous integration/continuous deployment (CI/CD)** for model updates, as implied by the **calibration-driven refinement** process. **Availability/reliability assurance** relies on **redundant hardware** (e.g., backup Raspberry Pi or cloud failover) and **deterministic real-time scheduling** for critical control tasks, though specifics like **SLA guarantees** or **uptime metrics** are absent."
]